name: Passage Proofreading: The Crocodile and The Monkey (Mythology)
description: Proofread a passage correcting ten mixed up adjectives and adverbs.
data:
"body"=>"--- \"There once was a crocodile living with his mother in a river. One day, the mother said, \\\"Darling, please go catch the monkey who lives in that tree and bring his heart to me for supper.\\\"\\r\\n\\r\\nThe crocodile {+quickly-(quick / quickly)|86} swam near the tree and shouted, \\\"Monkey, are you there? Let's go to the other side of the river where we will find trees full of {+ripe-(ripe / ripely)|85} fruit that I know you will enjoy.\\\"\\r\\n\\r\\n\\\"I don't know how to swim,\\\" replied the monkey.\\r\\n\\r\\n\\\"Just hop on my back,\\\" said the smiling crocodile. \\\"It will be my pleasure to carry you.\\\" The monkey was very hungry, so he {+gladly-(gladly / glad)|86} jumped down on the crocodile's back.\\r\\n\\r\\nInstead of swimming across the river, however, the crocodile started swimming to his mother. The monkey was alarmed and shouted, \\\"Crocodile, what are you doing?\\\"\\r\\n\\r\\n\\\"I'm taking you to my mother,\\\" said the crocodile, \\\"so that she can eat your heart for a {+delicious-(delicious / deliciously)|85} supper.\\\"\\r\\n\\r\\n\\\"Oh,\\\" said the monkey, \\\"then I should have brought my heart with me.\\\"\\r\\n\\r\\nThe {+young-(young / youngly)|85} crocodile was surprised. \\\"You don't have your heart with you now?\\\"\\r\\n\\r\\nThe monkey {+wittily-(witty / wittily)|88} replied, \\\"No, I left my heart at home. If you want, we can go back there and I'll get it.\\\"\\r\\n\\r\\nThe foolish crocodile agreed and {+slowly-(slowly / slow)|86} swam back towards the monkey's home. When they arrived, the monkey leaped up and landed {+safely-(safely / safe)|90} in the tree.\\r\\n\\r\\n\\\"And now, crocodile,\\\" the monkey {+happily-(happily / happy)|88} shouted, \\\"go away and leave me alone! You won't be able to trick me so {+easily-(easily / easy)|88} ever again.\\\"\" ", "instructions"=>"--- Choose the correct adjective or adverb from the parentheses.

To make changes, click on a word and delete the incorrect answer as well as the dash \"/\" and the parentheses. ... "

In the nearby fields,{+deer,-deers,|60} {+sheep,-sheeps,|61} {+mice,-mouses,|58} and other small animals fled from the gust. All the {+men,-mans,|54} women, and {+children-childs|56} hid in their houses, clenching their {+teeth-tooths|57} in fear, as the water filled the inside of each volcano. That night, the water shot back out into the ocean, and has risen and fallen with the tides ever since. ... name: Passage Proofreading: Janet Sends a Letter (Fiction)

data:
"body"=>"--- \"\\\"Excuse me, could you help me send this letter?\\\"\\r\\n\\r\\nJanet turned around and saw a nice old lady smiling behind her. The old lady was holding out a piece of paper towards Janet. Janet took the paper and looked at it. The address was not filled in, but the letter was beautifully hand written. \\r\\n\\r\\n\\\"I would love to help you,\\\" said Janet. She took a pen out of her purse and asked the lady, \\\"Where do you want to send the letter?\\\" The old lady replied, {+\\\"52 Fenway Street, Fieldspring, Massachusetts 12345.-\\\"52 Fenway Street Fieldspring Massachusetts 12345.|163} My grandson lives there.\\\" \\r\\n\\r\\nJanet started writing it out, but stopped halfway through.\\r\\n\\\"Are you sure your grandson's address is {+52 Fenway Street, Fieldspring, Massachusetts?\\\"-52 Fenway Street Fieldspring Massachusetts?\\\"|163}\\r\\n\\r\\n\\\"Did I say I Fieldspring? I'm sorry. Here is his real address: {+52 Fenway Street, Springfield, Massachusetts 12345.\\\"-52 Fenway Street Springfield Massachusetts 12345.\\\"|163} Janet finished writing the address and handed the letter back to the old lady.\\r\\n\\r\\n\\\"Thank you so much!\\\" the old lady said.\\r\\n\\r\\n\\\"Happy to help!\\\" replied Janet.\" ", "instructions"=>"--- \"
Insert commas into the addresses in the story.

Alex likes the mountains more, so he suggested doing a report on them.\\r\\n\\r\\nAlex and Vera went to do some research for their project. Unfortunately, {+neither-___|169} the library nor the bookstore was open that day, so it seemed as though the two would have to wait to finish their work. Luckily for Alex, Vera is {+not only-___|168} a fast reader, but also a great writer. Alex was not worried about finishing the project on time.\\r\\n\\r\\nThe next day both Alex and Vera went to the library. They found three great books about the Rocky Mountains. By the end of the day {+both-___|170} Alex and Vera knew all about the Rocky Mountains, and completing their project was a breeze.\" ", "instructions"=>"--- In this passage, the blanks need to be filled with appropriate words depending on which correlative conjunction is used.

  give me food for my donkeys at no cost. My workers are {+poor-pour|202} slaves and
  I pay them no wages for taking care of the donkeys. I {+lose-loose|209} no profit
  anywhere. That means I am able to sell my donkeys at the lowest possible price,
  but even {+then-than|207} you sell your donkeys for even less. {+It's-Its|211} unreasonable!
  How can that be?\\\"\\r\\n\\r\\nNasreddin smiled at the merchant and explained, {+\\\"You're-\\\"Your|208}

name: Passage Proofreading: One Giant Leap for Mankind (History)
description: Proofread a passage ensuring that the proper word is used in each circumstance.
data:
"body"=>"--- \"On July 16th, 1969, hundreds of people traveled to the Kennedy Space Center in Florida to watch the Launch of the Apollo 11 rocket. Speakers announced, “You {+may-(can / may)|119} not approach the launch site without permission.” Nine and a half years ago, President John F. Kennedy promised we would land a man on the Moon in the next 10 years. Today was the last chance America had to keep its promise. NASA knew they {+must-(must / should)|120} launch the rocket now, or they would run out of time. The crew asked Mission Control if they {+may-(may / can)|119} begin the countdown to launch. It was a perfect day for flying, so NASA knew there {+should-(should / must)|120} not be any problems.\\r\\n\\r\\nAfter a rocket leaves Earth, there is nothing else Mission Control {+can-(may / can)|119} do, so the launch is always tense. Once the rocket was close to the Moon, Mission Control told the crew they {+must-(must / should)|120} circle the moon once, because that was the only way to slow down. NASA suggested that they {+should-(should / must)|120} try to find some good rocks to bring back.\\r\\n\\r\\nTwo of the crew members, Neil Armstrong and Buzz Aldrin, launched a smaller ship from the Apollo 11 rocket, and landed on the Moon. When Neil Armstrong first stepped out of the ship he said, “That's one small step for a man, and one giant leap for mankind.”\" ", "instructions"=>"--- Rewrite the story by choosing the correct words from the parentheses.

Remember to delete the parentheses before clicking the submit button. ... "

name: Passage Proofreading: Nā ʻaumākua (History)
description: Proofread a passage and correct any mistakes in parallel structure.
data:
"body"=>"--- \"The ancient Hawaiian people were not as technologically advanced as other cultures
  of the time. However, by the time western civilization began communicating with
  the Hawaiian people, they had already developed a rich cultural heritage. They went
  about their lives by surviving off of the land, following strict social rules, and
  {+respecting-respected|196} their aumakuas, or \\\"family gods.\\\" Unlike more powerful
  deities, such as Pele, the fiery goddess of volcanoes, aumakuas interacted specifically
  with individual families as spiritual guides. They were known for appearing in peoples'
  dreams, {+save-saving|213} people from harm, and bringing about good fortune to
  people in need.\\r\\n\\r\\nLike the spirit guides of other religions, aumakuas were
  said to be able to shape-shift. They could appear as a shark lurking on the ocean
  floor, or a hawk circling the skies. However, they were said to make themselves
  known easily to anyone who worshipped them. Out of respect for these spirit guides,
  the Hawaiian people payed tribute to them, asked for their guidance, and {+considered-consider|195}
  them to be family.\"
", "instructions"=>"--- In this passage, there are three actions that do not agree with the other actions
  in their respective lists. To edit the text, click on a word and type your changes.
...
"

data:
"body"=>"--- \"It is Tuesday afternoon and Samir has been looking forward to going to the baseball game all day. He looks at his watch and sees that it's 3:15 PM on {+September 14th, 2012.-September 14th 2012.|45} As the game is about to start, Samir decides to find a good seat so that he can see {+Alex Rodriguez, Derek Jeter, and Ichiro Suzuki,-Alex Rodriguez Derek Jeter and Ichiro Suzuki,|46} his favorite players. \\r\\n\\r\\nBy the fourth inning, Samir is hungry so he goes to get something to eat. He orders a pretzel and a hotdog with {+ketchup, relish, and onions.-ketchup relish and onions.|46} The man behind the counter sees Samir wearing a Yankees hat, and gives him a free soda because he also likes the Yankees.\\r\\n\\r\\nJust as Samir sits back down, he hears the crack of a bat and the 'ooohhh' of the crowd. He sees that a foul ball is coming right toward him, and that none other than Derek Jeter is standing at the plate. His hands are full with the {+hotdog, soda, and pretzel,-hotdog soda and pretzel,|46} but he manages to catch the foul ball with the hotdog dish. The hotdog flops off the dish, but Samir manages to hold onto the foul ball. The crowd laughs as he holds up the foul ball, now covered in ketchup. \" ", "instructions"=>"---

data:
"body"=>"--- \"\\\"Devon, could you help me with this recipe?\\\"\\r\\n\\r\\nDevon's mom did not usually ask for his help, so he thought that this must be important. Devon went downstairs to the kitchen where his mom was cooking.\\r\\n\\r\\n\\\"Devon, I can't mix the ingredients and read the recipe at the same time. Could you read the instructions to me out loud?\\\"\\r\\n\\r\\n\\\"No problem, mom.   king's oldest adviser proclaimed, \\\"I think we should drown the creature by throwing
  it into the deepest part of the lake!\\\"\\r\\n\\r\\nAt this point, the turtle spoke up

  waters! I {+don't-dont|98} care if you pound me with {+a-an|29} hammer or throw

President Kennedy decided this was the course his country should be taking, and planning began to make America the first nation on earth to land a man on the moon.\\r\\n\\r\\nOn September 12th, 1962, just a little over a year after President Kennedy asked Vice President Johnson what America could do to rival the Soviet space program, Kennedy gave a speech at Rice University in Texas. As Kennedy was {+delivering-(to deliver)|116} his speech, known as the \\\"We Choose the Moon\\\" speech, he was {+detailing-(detail)|116} why he believed America should be the first to reach the moon. He also promised that America would land a man on the moon within the next ten years. When he finished his 18 minute speech, President Kennedy officially started the race to the moon. description: Proofread a passage correcting eight errors with irregular plural nouns and verbs. This passage covers Common Core concepts 2.1b and 2.1d.
data:
"body"=>"--- \"Many years ago Sun and Water were great friends that both lived on Earth together.
  Sun often visited Water, but Water never went to visit Sun. When Sun asked Water
  why she never {+came-comed|73} to visit him, Water replied that Sun’s house was
  not big enough for her and all her {+children-childs|56} that lived in Water. Water
  told Sun that if he wanted her to visit, he would have to build a house big enough
  for her and all the {+fish-fishes|53} and other creatures. Sun agreed, returned
  home to his wife, Moon, and together they {+built-builded|72} a big house so that
  they could entertain Water.\\r\\n\\r\\nThe next day, Sun and Moon asked Water to visit.
  When she arrived, Water {+spoke-speaked|342} to Sun, asking, “Is it safe for me
  to enter?” Sun answered, “Yes, come in, my friend!” Then Water started to flow in,
  followed by all the plants and animals that live in the seas, rivers, and ponds
  of the world. \\r\\n\\r\\nSoon, Water was knee deep, and Water asked Sun, “Is it still
  safe?” Sun answered, “Yes, of course! Come in.” When Water was as tall as a man,
  she asked, “Do you have room for the rest of my friends?” Both Sun and his wife,
  Moon, answered, “Yes,” but they never {+knew-knowed|346} how many creatures lived
  in Water. Water was full of {+shrimp,-shrimps,|53} {+salmon,-salmons,|53} and other
  {+fish.-fishes.|53}\\r\\n\\r\\nEventually, Water and all her creatures filled the house,
  so Sun and Moon {+sat-sitted|81} on the roof. Water asked Sun again, “Is there still
  enough room?” This time, Water received no reply, so her friends continued to enter
  Sun and Moon’s house. Water soon overflowed out of the windows and doors of the
  house and streamed over the roof. Sun and Moon were forced to go up into the sky,
  where they have lived ever since.\"
", "instructions"=>"--- Find and correct 10 errors.

  suits with the vacuum of space in {+mind, so-mind so|24} the moment that Leonov
  began his EVA his suit began to slowly inflate.  By just 10 minutes into the {+spacewalk,-spacewalk|239}
  Leonov noticed his suit had became so swollen that he was unable to reach the lock
  where the door handle was.\\r\\n\\r\\nLeonov knew he had to act fast, so he decided
  to make a risky move. He opened up a pressure valve in his suit to try to bleed
  off some of the excess pressure. Despite the danger of the maneuver, Leonov managed
  to release enough pressure {+that-where|110} he was able to safely re-enter the
  rocket.  \\r\\n\\r\\nOnce Leonov was back inside the craft, the two cosmonauts {+then-than|207}
  worked {+quickly-quick|86} to prepare their ship to return to earth. What the men

  they took an additional 46 seconds to get the {+ship's-ships|165} center of gravity
  into the correct position to re-enter earth's atmosphere. The delay caused the ship
  to fly off course, and the two men landed in the inhospitable Soviet tundra.\\r\\n\\r\\nWhen
  the craft landed, the forest cover was so dense that the {+Soviets-Soviet's|228}

description: Proofread a passage and correct any confused words.
data:
"body"=>"--- \"The English word pirate is derived from the Greek word πειρατής (peirates), which
  meant a robber, especially a robber at sea. In ancient times, pirates sailed the
  Mediterranean, and many stories were told about those pirates. There is a famous
  legend about the god Dionysus and some pirates, for example, and there is also a
  famous story about Alexander the Great and a pirate named Diomedes.\\r\\n\\r\\nDiomedes,
  so the story tells us, was a notorious pirate who had finally been captured and
  brought before the emperor for sentencing. Because of the pirate's many criminal
  deeds, everyone expected that Alexander would sentence the pirate to death and {+cleanse-cleans|204}
  the seas of his evil.  Before he passed judgment, however, Alexander decided to
  interview the pirate.\\r\\n\\r\\n{+\\\"Although-\\\"All though|199} I am inclined to be
  done with you, I must ask, what could possibly give you the right to sail the seas,
  marauding merchants and taking {+their-there|212} goods?\\\" Alexander asked the pirate.\\r\\n\\r\\nDiomedes
  boldly replied with some questions of his own. \\\"O Emperor,\\\" he said, \\\"what could
  possibly give you the right to travel the whole world, taking by force things that
  do not belong to you? What gave you the right to occupy the land of Egypt? Who made
  you king of Persia? {+Finally,-Finely,|201} by what authority did you invade the
  land of India?\\r\\n\\r\\nAlexander sat on this {+throne-thrown|197} and stared at the
  man in amazement. Diomedes went on speaking. \\\"Because I use only my own boat,\\\"
  he said, \\\"I am called a pirate. You, however, use your army and your navy, and
  so you are proclaimed an emperor. If you ask me who is the greater criminal, I cannot
  say. I do know, however, that if I had such weapons at my disposal, I would be an
  emperor {+too.\\\"-two.\\\"|210}\\r\\n\\r\\nAlexander was so impressed by this reply that
  instead of punishing the pirate, he let him go, praising him for his boldness and
  insight. It was a rare thing to meet a man who said what he {+meant.-mint.|198}\"
